1167":"1167","1145":"1145","ABT 1080":"okolo 1080","İznik, Bursa, Turkey":"İznik, Bursa, Turecko","Gent, Flandre-Orientale, Belgique":"Gent, Oost-Vlaanderen, Belgie","Belgium":"Belgie","Europe":"Europe","Schoten, Antwerp, Belgium":"Schoten, Antwerpen, Belgie","Pays-Bas":"Nizozemsko"},"da":{"1086–1131":"1086–1131","1090–1145":"1090–1145","1075–1167":"1075–1167","1104–1152":"1104–1152","1110–1165":"1110–1165","1062–1097":"1062–1097","1060–Female":"1060–Afdød","before 1105":"før 1105","1090":"1090","environ 1110":"omkring 1110","1165":"1165","1110":"1110","1131":"1131","1086":"1086","1097":"1097","1152":"1152","1075":"1075","1062":"1062","13 June 1097":"13. juni 1097","1060":"1060","1104":"1104","1167":"1167","1145":"1145","ABT 1080":"omkring 1080","İznik, Bursa, Turkey":"İznik, Bursa, Tyrkiet","Gent, Flandre-Orientale, Belgique":"Gent, Oost-Vlaanderen, Belgien","Belgium":"Belgien","Europe":"Europe","Schoten, Antwerp, Belgium":"Schoten, Antwerpen, Belgien","Pays-Bas":"Nederlandene"},"nl":{"1086–1131":"1086–1131","1090–1145":"1090–1145","1075–1167":"1075–1167","1104–1152":"1104–1152","1110–1165":"1110–1165","1062–1097":"1062–1097","1060–Female":"1060–Overleden","before 1105":"vóór 1105","1090":"1090","environ 1110":"circa 1110","1165":"1165","1110":"1110","1131":"1131","1086":"1086","1097":"1097","1152":"1152","1075":"1075","1062":"1062","13 June 1097":"13 juni 1097","1060":"1060","1104":"1104","1167":"1167","1145":"1145","ABT 1080":"circa 1080","İznik, Bursa, Turkey":"İznik, Bursa, Turkije","Gent, Flandre-Orientale, Belgique":"Gent, Oost-Vlaanderen, België","Belgium":"België","Europe":"Europa","Schoten, Antwerp, Belgium":"Schoten, Antwerpen, België","Pays-Bas":"Nederland"},"en":{"1086–1131":"1086–1131","1090–1145":"1090–1145","1075–1167":"1075–1167","1104–1152":"1104–1152","1110–1165":"1110–1165","1062–1097":"1062–1097","1060–Female":"1060–Deceased","before 1105":"before 1105","1090":"1090","environ 1110":"about 1110","1165":"1165","1110":"1110","1131":"1131","1086":"1086","1097":"1097","1152":"1152","1075":"1075","1062":"1062","13 June 1097":"13 June 1097","1060":"1060","1104":"1104","1167":"1167","1145":"1145","ABT 1080":"about 1080","İznik, Bursa, Turkey":"İznik, Bursa, Türkiye","Gent, Flandre-Orientale, Belgique":"Gent, East Flanders, Belgium","Belgium":"Belgium","Europe":"Europe","Schoten, Antwerp, Belgium":"Schoten, Antwerp, Belgium","Pays-Bas":"Netherlands","nameMeanings":[{"name":"VAN","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Vietnamese Anh, Thanh, Hung, Minh, Vinh, Dung, Hue, Huong, Lan, Quang, Tan, Thuy, Hong, Chi, Hang, Ho, Pok, Sang, Bai, Chin, Ching, Chu, Chuan, Dong.","Vietnamese (<b>Vạn</b>): from the Chinese surname 萬, see   Wan   1.","Vietnamese (<b>Văn</b>): from the Chinese surnames 文 or 聞, see   Wen   2 and 3, and also 5 below."],"variants":[{"name":"Wan","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Yi, Qi, Qiang, Wai, Yiu, Yuk, Chien-Min, Fang, Hin, Jichun, Li, Man, Chung, Min, Yiping, Pak, Sik, Sung Man.  Vietnamese Tin, Bang, Da, Hien, Hoi, Lan, Minh Quang, Sau, Tich, Tung, Yaping, Yuet.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 萬, which means ‘ten thousand’ literally or ‘very great number’ figuratively: (i) from the personal name of Bi Wan (畢萬), an official in the state of Jin (located in present-day Shanxi province). He was said to be a descendant of Bi Gong Gao (known as Duke of Bi), the 15th son of the virtuous King Wen of Zhou (reined 1152–1056  BC ). Bi Wan was later granted the fiefdom of Wei (魏), which in 403  BC  became the state of Wei (located in present-day Shanxi, Shaanxi, Henan and Hebei provinces). Some of his descendants adopted Wei (魏) as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his personal name, as their surname. (ii) from the personal name Wan (萬), style name of Rui Bo (芮伯, the Earl of Rui), an official of the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ), who was granted the fief Rui (located in Ruicheng in Shaanxi province). Some of his descendants inherited Rui (芮), the name of the fief, as their surname, while others inherited 萬 (Wan), his style name, as their surname. (iii) from the placename Wan (萬), the name of a fief (located in Juxian in Shandong province) granted during the Spring and Autumn period (770–476  BC ) to an official in the ancient state of Chu. (iv) from the first element of the name of the Wan Si (萬俟) family, who lived in the downstream areas of the Yellow River during the Northern Qi dynasty (550–577  AD ). (v) from the second element of the name of the Tu Wan (吐萬) family, who are members of the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 完, meaning ‘complete’ in Chinese: (i) said to be borne by the descendants of Huan Zhui, a grandson of the Duke Huan of Song (ruler of the state of Song, died 651  BC ). (ii) from Wan (完), the name of Qu Wan (屈完), an official in the state of Chu during the Spring and Autumn Period (770–476  BC ). (iii) shortened form of the compound surname Wan-Yan (完顔), a surname from minority ethnic groups such as Juchen ethnic group in ancient northern China."]}]},{"name":"Adèle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."],"variants":[{"name":"Adel","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]},{"name":"Adelle","meanings":["From French  <b>Adèle</b> , an ancient name popular in medieval Europe because of the fame of a 7th-century saint, a daughter of the Frankish king Dagobert II. It is of Germanic origin, from <i>adal</i> ‘noble’ (a short form of a two-element name such as <i>Adelheid</i>;  see  Adelaide  ). It was the name of William the Conqueror's youngest daughter (  <i>c.</i>1062–1137 ), who became the wife of Stephen of Blois. However, it died out in England in the later Middle Ages. It was revived in the 19th century, being the name of a character in  Johann Strauss's  opera Die Fledermaus. Its popularity was further reinforced in the 1930s as the name of a character in the novels of  Dornford Yates ."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Adèle VAN AALST-GENT was born in 1086, in Gent, East Flanders, Belgium, her father, Boudewijn II van Gent, was 25 and her mother, Regnevide dit “Reina de Cassel” van Aalst, dame de Gand, was 27. She married Hendrik Reinier van Brunesheim before 1105, in Europe. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 1 daughter. She died in 1131, in Netherlands, at the age of 45."},"et":{"1086–1131":"1086–1131","1090–1145":"1090–1145","1075–1167":"1075–1167","1104–1152":"1104–1152","1110–